deck_description: Dark Magician deck to beat my friend
Infernoble, Flame Swordsman and Azamina. Still trying to find the right balance.

Primite provides a useful Rank 4 engine that lets you go into either Merrymaker+Sarger (for Regulus) or Dempsey (for Air Lifter). Also, Drillbeam is a crazy card.

The main line you are looking to do is:

  1. Have Hydrant, a body, and Lode on field (example: opening Beryl + Emergency)
  2. Link Hydrant into Clockwork Knight
  3. Send Lode to search Clockwork Night
  4. Link into Barricade -> pitch Night
  5. Banish Night -> Search Regulus
  6. End phase add back Lode

This is fairly easy to thread into the standard R-ACE link climbing with Preventer into Promethean.

Side deck cards are just flex Extra decks choices. E.g. Link Spider is nice for S:P, Controller is nice if you only open Beryl (make Sargas, link into Controller, summon Regulus), etc.

deck_excerpt: Soar of the Blue-Eyes White Dragon
deck_description:
Playing style[edit]

The "Blue-Eyes" archetype centers on the Level 8 LIGHT Dragon Normal Monster, "Blue-Eyes White Dragon", swarming the field with it, and/or using it to create various Main Deck or Extra Deck boss monsters. Many support cards mention the original "Blue-Eyes White Dragon" specifically, while most in-theme Extra Deck monsters require a "Blue-Eyes" monster or the original "Blue-Eyes White Dragon".

The archetype's boss monsters can be broadly divided by their card typing: Main Deck non-Ritual, Ritual, Fusion, Synchro, Xyz, and Link.

  • Main Deck non-Ritual: They generally have field control or supportive effects, and help get Level 8 and 10 "Blue-Eyes" monsters on field to use for Ritual/Fusion/Synchro/Xyz/Link plays. Examples include "Blue-Eyes Alternative White Dragon", "Dragon Spirit of White", "Deep-Eyes White Dragon", "Blue-Eyes Abyss Dragon", "Blue-Eyes Solid Dragon", "Blue-Eyes Jet Dragon" and "Blue-Eyes Shining Dragon".
  • Ritual: Consisting of "Blue-Eyes Chaos MAX Dragon" and "Blue-Eyes Chaos Dragon", they are Level 8 Ritual Monsters focus on performing OTKs by dealing massive piercing damage, while having a protective effect that prevents them from being targeted or destroyed by the opponent's card effects. They synergize with the Ritual Spell "Chaos Form".
  • Fusion: Consisting of "Blue-Eyes Ultimate Dragon", "Blue-Eyes Twin Burst Dragon", "Neo Blue-Eyes Ultimate Dragon", "Blue-Eyes Alternative Ultimate Dragon" and "Blue-Eyes Tyrant Dragon", they require 2 or 3 "Blue-Eyes White Dragon" as materials. They focus on performing OTKs by having large ATK and being able to attack multiple times, and/or focus on controlling the field by having strong protections and the ability to remove opposing cards.
  • Synchro: Consisting of "Blue-Eyes Ultimate Spirit Dragon" and "Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon", they are 9 and 12 Synchro Monsters that focus on controlling the field by providing situational floodgating, effect negation, monster protection, and monster revival. "Spirit Dragon" notably can Tribute itself to Special Summon any LIGHT Dragon Synchro Monster from the Extra Deck as a Quick Effect, giving it significant flexibility.
  • Xyz: Only consisting of "Indigo-Eyes Silver Dragon".
  • Link: Only consisting of "Spirit with Eyes of Blue".

The archetype's main lower-level support monsters are all Level 1 LIGHT Tuner monsters, and can be divided into two types: the with Eyes of Blue Spellcasters, and the "White Stone" Dragons ("The White Stone of Ancients" and "The White Stone of Legend"). The "with Eyes of Blue" monsters focus on searching and interacting with Level 1 LIGHT Tuners and Special Summoning "Blue-Eyes" monsters, while the "White Stone" monsters gain advantage when sent to the GY.

The card attributes that surround "Blue-Eyes White Dragon" (Level 8, LIGHT, Dragon, Normal Monster) gives it a large amount of external support, such as "Trade-In", "The Melody of Awakening Dragon", "Dragon Shrine", "Dragon Ravine", "Silver's Cry", and "Return of the Dragon Lords". Also, as it frequently summons Level 8 monsters, it can benefit from the generic Rank 8 pool.

In competitive play[edit]

In terms of competitive play, "Blue-Eyes" can be split into two rough categories: Synchro and Chaos MAX.

Synchro variants aim to go first, gaining field presence with Synchro monsters such as "Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon", "Blue-Eyes Ultimate Spirit Dragon", and other Dragon Synchro monsters like "Cosmic Blazar Dragon" (summoned using "Crimson Dragon"). This was the variant that won the World Championships in 2016; it helped that "Spirit Dragon" countered many of the then-meta Decks (its GY negate hurt "Burning Abyss", the "Neither player can Special Summon 2 or more monsters" effect countered Pendulum), and that those Decks were nerfed by the banlist. With the release of Structure Deck: Advent of the Eyes of Blue in the OCG, as well as the Normal Monster-supporting "Primite" engine, this variant gained major support, giving it success in the current meta.

Chaos MAX variants, meanwhile, focus on an OTK using the power of "Blue-Eyes Chaos MAX Dragon". At the time, "Chaos MAX's" destruction and targeting protection made it a difficult monster to get rid of, giving it some rogue-level success.

Also, when "Dragon Rulers" were dominant, a small Blue-Eyes engine - consisting of "Blue-Eyes White Dragon", "The White Stone of Legend", as well as draw cards "Trade-In" and "Cards of Consonance" - were sometimes used for advantage. They could be used as discards to supplement "Super Rejuvenation", banished from the GY to summon the "Dragon Rulers", and possibly summoned with "Soul Charge" to make Rank 8s.

Weaknesses[edit]

  • As an archetype that consists primarily of LIGHT and Dragon monsters, specific Attribute and typing counters, such as "Ally of Justice", "Light-Imprisoning Mirror" or "Bystial" monsters can significantly hamper the deck's performance.
  • As most of the key cards of this archetype are either high-level monsters or a low-level searchers with low stats, the player is likely to have dead draws or a bricked hand that reduce the deck's consistency, if not unable to make any plays. (As of recent support in the OCG, this issue has mostly been mitigated, with Blue-Eyes variants now able to perform "1-card" and "2-card" combos with help of the new Primite engine)

Cheap (cheaper with piri instead of nightmare throne) but definitely not bad deckprofile with beckoning beast as a one card combo for unchained. The one card combo works: Throne add beckoning, normal beckoning and add spirit gates, spirit gates adds second beckoning and then do your second normalsummon to go for Yama. Yama adds Sharvara, then discard sharvara for Spirit Gates to special out of grave and set a Unchained card. Now Link for Super Producer and destroy your Spirit Gates to trigger Yama in GY. Special Sharvara and destroy the trap, then play as usual. You could play a small Yubel engine consisting of 1 Spirit of Yubel,1 Yubel in maindeck and 1 Phantom of Yubel in extra deck if you already have beckoning beast in hand combined with nightmare throne but be aware that you may add grave squirmer to play through imperm on beckoning beast to get the second body on field for yama.

deck_excerpt: Can't afford primite? Here you go!
deck_description: This is a Blue-Eyes Invoked list. This is probably one of, if not the, best budget variant of blue eyes, maybe not this build specifically. This build was made very neutral, without a specific meta in mind (also the reason I didn't include a side deck). So it can be modified easily to fit the current meta. This version does solve one problem the primite version has, and that's nibiru. As this deck can get out mechaba on it's third summon, as long as you have another monster in hand, nibiru can't hurt you (as much as it would without mechaba). It also of course helps you can make the blue-eyes link 1 with aleister. So just normal Aleister, search Invocation, link into spirit, do the normal things with spirit, and then go into mechaba with both aleister and spirit in grave. Hope you have fun with it.

deck_excerpt: D.D. Post + Necroface + zombies. Mill to banishment and beatdown.
deck_description:
Shoutout to Kip Landon on Dueling Nexus for the original idea. Think their original build was more of an OTK Necroface banish/mill build with Shiranuis but I bricked frequently using that build so I built out this modified version. Still tweaking ratios but super fun to play.

  • General idea is to get as many D.D. Posts on the field as quickly as possible and to banish necroface as much as possible to mill as many of your cards + opponent's cards into banishment. Shiranuis help generate card advantage off this banish/mill from necroface.
  • D.D. Post is super powerful in this build because:
    • Each one gives your monsters a 900 ATK boost turnning even weak starters into 2000+ ATK beaters and boosting your boss monsters up enough to swing over almost any other monster.
    • Each one gives you 1 banish from GY and 1 return from banishment to deck. That means every turn you can generate card advantage by banishing necroface to mill, banishing shiranui zombies for their effects, or banishing other zombies like changshi and alghoul for their effects. 
    • If D.D. Post is banished (Ex. off a necroface mill or off another D.D. Post's effect) you can activate it on your field.
    • D.D. Post is an all-in-one offensive tool, control tool, and recursion tool depending on what you banish and what you return.
  • Milling to banishment is typically bad but the shiranui package in this deck helps give you card advantage off those banishes while your opponent loses key combo pieces from their deck.
  • Use shiranuis and zombies to step into synchro and link monsters.
  • Usually the combo of the necroface mill + beatdown by the powered up monsters can over run any deck.

Will add some starters / combos and synergies later. Deck still needs a bit of tweaking because it sometimes doesn't setup a great board and isn't the best at going second. A very unique zombies strat though because it doesn't special summon from GY that often so opponent's unfamiliar with the build will likely be confused.

I think adding more Zombie World support could be helpful here, bc doom king helps the build a lot when he's live, and maybe at least one revive from GY. Also tweaking some of the extra deck. Maybe also Rivalry of Warlords as an additional floodgate. Could also be funny as a skill drain deck. Side deck are other cards I'm playing around with. Also current cost of deck is super cheap!

deck_name: Mid-core competitive Blue Eyes deck( No Primite)
deck_description:
General tips:

Sage and Maiden are starters.

Both can set you up for a ultimate spirit and cosmic blazer end board uninterrupted. If something goes wrong, the bystial lubellion can be used as a substitute for your non tuner.

Piri reis map can also search sage and if drawn with a starter can always be used for the wishes discard.

The buster lock package is included in the side deck as it's searchable through sage and is very hard to out,but can be bricky. Standard charmys, solemn and board breakers can replace this package. 

Dragons bind can be devastating if used with a bystial and is also a card you can put to 3 instead of the buster lock.

If you remove the buster lock cards replace buster welp in the extra deck with the hot red archfiend abyss to summon with crimson dragon.

Deck is very weak to droll consider cross-out as another side option

Don't worry about banishing the vanilla blue eyes prior to using roar as it can summon from banishment.

deck_description:
A gamebreaking splashable engine has entered into the Masterduel meta - Fiendsmith! For the most part, we've seen "FTK" style combo decks like Snake-Eyes, Yubel and Tearlaments put this guy into their strategies to make a powerful endboard negate boss monsters like Desirae or D/D/D Wave High King Caesar. Fiendsmith can also increase consistency of combo decks capable making rank 6s like Beatrice or Pilgrim Reaper. I personally find that BORING!!!
 
What if we used Fiendsmith to power-up a low-to-the-ground control strategy? Bystial Fiendsmith takes exactly this philosophy and cracks the power up to 11! This ridiculous control strategy has TWENTY-FIVE handtraps to interrupt your opponent's plans to a standstill. It also punches back extremely hard since Bystials are naturally giant 2500ATK beatsticks and Desirae can be up to 3400ATK! If that's not enough, Accesscode Talker with 2-3 pops is easily accessible in this build, especially with Cyberse Gadget's materials in the GY. 
 
There won't be a in-depth strategy/combo guide for this deck since it basically just all handtraps. You might think this deck is inconsistent and bricky, but it isn't! This is because the basic play is 2 monsters = full Fiendsmith combo with Moon of the Closed Heaven, and bodies are easy to get on the board with Bystials. The win condition is winning out on top during the handtrap minigame played between you and your opponent, and as your opponent watches as you out-resource them in Bystials and Fiendsmith's recursive grindgame, that's usually enough to convince them to surrender. As for Cyberse Gadget, you just summon your link-1s to make 2 bodies on-field and eventually make Moon of the Closed Heaven. 
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
Since 10 Bystials are used in this decklist, here is a guide on when/where to handtrap common ladder match-ups optimally:
 
Fiendsmith - When your opponent activates Engraver in the GY to summon it, banish it with a bystial. When your opponent only has 2 materials in the GY (they're attempting to summon Lacrima) and they activate Sequence's effect to fusion summon, banish one of the fusion materials with a bystial to stop the fusion summon. 
 
Snake-Eyes - When your opponent activates Flamberge Dragon to place I:P Masquerena in the backrow, banish it with a bystial. If you have an extra Bystial, when your opponent activate Linkuriboh's effect to summon itself from the GY, banish it with a bystial. 
 
Yubel - When your opponent has Unchained Soul of Yama in the GY, banish it with a Bystial. When your opponent attempts to summon from the GY using Abominable Chamber of the Unchained, banish the summon target with a bystial. When your opponent attempts to summon from the GY using Opening of the Spirit Gates, banish the summon target with abystial. When you anticipate your opponent making Phantom of Yubel with their GY materials, banish it with a bystial. 
 
White Forest - When your opponent attempts to summon either Rucia/Silvy from the GY by returning their Synchro monster to the Extra Deck, banish either with a bystial. 
 
Azamina - When your opponent activates The Hallowed Azamina in the GY to add it back to hand by returning an Azamina fusion/Elzette Azamina back to the Extra Deck/Deck, banish the targeted Azamina with a bystial. 
 
Branded - When the Albion monster attempts to fusion summons another monster, banish Fallen of Albaz with a Bystial. Before your opponent enters End Phase, banish their End Phase monsters in the GY (Albion, Titaniklad, Cartesia, etc.) with a bystial. Before your opponent summons Bystial Lubellion from the GY by tributing their dark dragon monster, banish it with a bystial. Banish Granguignol from the GY with a bystial. 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

deck_excerpt: Z-ARC really ties this thing together
deck_description:
A surprisingly flexible fusion of Dinomorphia and Ryu-Ge engines!

The emphasis on effects that destroy monsters is favorable for Mistva and the Dinomorphia monsters, Z-ARC tags out into Arcray which sets Mistva, and leaving room for link monsters means you can customize your backrow with Saryuja or board wipe with Zealantis (protip: Zealantis won't summon your opponent's monsters back the same turn you activate the field spell, unless they happen to be playing the same types of monsters as you)
Pure Mimighouls for the semi-sadistic fun of forcing opponents to pick their poison in a bit more of a casual way.
Just something I threw together to test
Basically my 2 favorite Fusion decks that work together and I finally made a list

Still testing, as long as you can get Fighting Flame Swordsman on the field you can get your combo rolling (unless they negate you, which sucks) 

Fighting Flame Sword, the search/negate spell that makes the deck, is hard to budget but if you can either get it in Japanese or somehow land a cheap copy (or three) it's well worth having

deck_description: A version of fiend fusion with greater focus on the illusion stuff + Azamina stuff.

An attempt to build Tenpai again as an actual deck, less focus on the Dragon Rulers and such. The basic goal is to use Ravine+Fadra to set up board breaking with Aiza and the Synchros. Runs a full removal sweet for dealing with the decks horrific ability to be interrupted.

Sort of a second attempt at Crystrons. The best negate in the format is Dragite, so the probable best deck at abusing it would be a Water Synchro deck, especially with Blaster. At least, that's the theory. Not sure how it'll handle in practice.

deck_excerpt: Powerful and fairly consistent Ice Barrier deck.
deck_description:
An Ice Barrier deck that I put together and tested in Master duel (as 99% of the deck is the same) as well as Duelingnexus. (I don't have a video for you, so I will describe the deck and it's main plays the best i can)

The main point of the deck is overwhelming your opponent with floodgate monsters and hand traps, leaving them open for your 3000+ attack monsters.


We have the standard package of 3 Georgius, Swordman of the Ice Barrier, 3 Revealer of the Ice Barrier, 3 Speaker for the Ice Barriers, 3 Mirror Mage of the Ice Barrier and 2 Hexa Spirit of the Ice Barrier (since their only use is getting Mirror Mage into the graveyard and maybe Warlock or Defender if you can get a Georgius on field to summon them), as well as 3 Icejade Ran Aegirine since they're an easy level 10 Synchro.
Icejade Tremora and Icejade Tinola serve as support for the entire deck since you can pitch Tremora to summon any Water monster from the hand, and Tinola as an emergency Monster reborn for any water monster in your Grave (as well as being a way to send Mirror Mage or Speaker to graveyard), with both being a special from the graveyard for Icejade Gymir Aegirine after it goes to the graveyard.

Your main play is going to be:
Revealer of the Ice Barrier discards card from hand, preferably Mirror Mage of the Ice Barrier (since it's your main searcher other than Medallion of the Ice Barrier), to summon Georgius, Swordman of the Ice Barrier from the deck. Chain 1: Georgius summons a level 5 or lower Ice Barrier from hand or graveyard, preferably Mirror Mage in the grave, Chain 2: Mirror Mage in the grave searches for Speaker for the Ice Barriers. Synchro Revealer+Georgius into Lancea, Ancestral Dragon of the Ice Mountain (your main boss monster). Special Speaker and use tribute effect of Mirror Mage to special 3 level 1 tokens and turn him into a level 5. Synchro Mirrormage+token into Coral Dragon, banish Speaker from the GY with its own effect to summon another level 1 token and Synchro into Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys for a 3+1 draw. Chain 1: Croc, Chain 2: Coral Dragon to chain block. Optimally you drew multiple hand traps.
(obviously if you couldn't get Mirror Mage into the graveyard you can't summon Croc, but you still have your Boss monster on field and posibly 1 floodgate Ice Barrier monster, which soon turns into 2; Alternatively, if you have a Georgius in hand you can special summon Mirror Mage with Revealer and then tribute her for a Adamancipator Risen - Dragite path, with Georgius resummoning the Revealer and you can make Lancea that way)

Your best on-field play is going to be the same, but you will also require another Georgius in hand (it can summon itself from the hand if you have an Ice Barrier monster on the field) as well as Freezing Chains of the Ice Barrier, Icejade Ran Aegirine and another water monster, preferably Icejade Tremora or Icejade Tinola for their graveyard effect to special an Icejade from the hand or graveyard, with the aim being of resummoning Icejade Gymir Aegirine, which can also resummon itself from the graveyard if your opponent banishes a card, making it a monster that can return twice in a turn as well as protect your monsters from effect destruction and banish, + banishes a card that used its effect if you chain it after the said card.
The field on your side can now consist of Lancea, Ancestral Dragon of the Ice Mountain, Icejade Gymir Aegirine, Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys and Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying, but you have to be careful of when you summon things as you can easily screw yourself over and block your zones. I'd suggest saving the Georgius in your hand until you summon Coral Dragon, and not after synchroing it into Croc since Lancea doesn't count as an Ice Barrier monster thus you have to have a token on field to summon Georgius.

Your best hand-trap play will consist of only the Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys path, since this way you can have the most handtraps possible.
The most common way to do this is to normal summon Hexa Spirit of the Ice Barrier and send Mirror Mage of the Ice Barrier into the graveyard to grab Speaker for the Ice Barriers to special summon it. Use Hexa and Speaker to summon Marincess Coral Anemone to summon Mirror Mage, which then tributes Anemone for tokens. (if you have Speaker in hand, grab Georgius, Swordman of the Ice Barrier instead to resummon Speaker and use both for Lancea, Ancestral Dragon of the Ice Mountain)

If you can't get Speaker into the Grave for the token, summon Adamancipator Risen - Dragite.
Summon Toadally Awesome with Bahamut Shark or 2 Mirror Mage of the Ice Barrier if you for any reason get 2 on the field.
If you have both Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying and Icejade Gymir Aegirine on the field you can banish 2 extra cards with Chengying (one from field and one from grave) after Gymir banishes a card as a response.

Use Lancea, Ancestral Dragon of the Ice Mountain to summon floodgate monsters like General Raiho of the Ice Barrier, Defender of the Ice Barrier, Spellbreaker of the Ice Barrier, and other Ice Barrier monsters with effects that hinder or stop your opponent. When it leaves your field you can synchro summon either Trishula, Zero Dragon of the Ice Barrier or Trishula, Dragon of the Ice Barrier depending on the situation. Again, this is your main boss monster and you should ALWAYS aim to summon it.

deck_excerpt: Budget deck. Exosisters is a deck which is a year old at best and Argostars are under supported. Put the two together for synergy.
deck_description:
Okay hear me out... The synergy is that the Exosister XYZ monsters are warriors which gain battle/card destruction protection and that any two level 4 monsters can move into Exosisters. Also Argostars can play on the opponents turn and don't have to special summon during your turn.

Combo 1: Start with Argostars - Glorious Adra and either of Exosister Pax , Exosister Returnia or Exosister Vadis .

- Normal Argostars - Glorious Adra , banish to place Argostars - Lightning Tydeu and Argostars - Swift Capane . Use Argostars - Lightning Tydeu  to discard a card and special, search Argostars - Slayer Eteo . Special Argostars - Swift Capane  and xyz into Exosister Mikailis . Use Exosister Mikailis to search either Exosister Returnia or Exosister Vadis . (Use Exosister Pax to find the missing peice). Set Argostars - Slayer Eteo and activate turn 2. Notice how this is 4 summons and plays under Nibiru, the Primal Being .

This leaves you with at least 1 banish from Exosister Returnia and a bounce to hand from Argostars - Slayer Eteo (remember to return to S&P zone). Also Exosister Mikailis is now protected from effect destruction by Argostars - Slayer Eteo . If you predict they will move out of graveyard, chain Exosister Vadis to special up to another Exosister Mikailis and Exosister Gibrine / Exosister Kaspitell (for an additional banish, negate/lock out of graveyard effects). Exosister Returnia now would give 2 banishes. Since this is a 3 card combo, hopefully you have 2 handtraps still. 

 

Combo 2: Start with Exosister Martha and Argostars - Glorious Adra .

Normal Argostars - Glorious Adra and banish to place Argostars - Slayer Eteo and Argostars - Swift Capane . If this is impermed or effect veilered, you can still send Argostars - Glorious Adra to banishment for cost, but the effect won't activate. Then special Exosister Martha and special Exosister Elis from deck, xyz into Exosister Mikailis and search Exosister Vadis / Exosister Returnia (note that Exosister Vadis probably will not work under Dimension Shifter . Don't be greedy and special Exosister Elis  if its in your hand, you can get Nibiru, the Primal Being .

Your end board composes of whatever benefit you get from Exosister Vadis / Exosister Returnia , and bounce to hand from Argostars - Slayer Eteo and battle and card destruction immunity on your xyz monsters.

 

Combo 3: Only Argostars - Glorious Adra 

Normal and banish, place Argostars - Slayer Eteo and Argostars - Lightning Tydeu . Discard for Argostars - Lightning Tydeu and add Argostars - Home Stadium . Activate it and end turn.

In you opponents turn, you can face up negate 2 card and bounce 1. It's not much but its something (plus you will have 3 extra hand traps waiting)

 

Combo 4: Only Exosisters ( Exosister Pax , Exosister Martha , Exosister Elis ).

If you can push further, use Exosister Kaspitell first to get materials for xyz summon of Exosister Mikailis ,then  Exosisters Magnifica . If possible, search Exosister Returnia , if not, end on Exosister Mikailis and Exosister Vadis . If all goes well, you have 4 banishes on your opponents turn for them to deal with. 

If you get ashed, impermed, effect veilered etc... your plays stop dead. This is 7 summons so you can get Nibiru, the Primal Being . No battle or card protection turn 2. Would avoid unless you have crossout/called by in hand, and even then this is a low priority.

 

Pros and Cons:

Its not much but pros: 

- Can play with dimension shifter

- Small engine (s), can run 20 handtraps/going second cards.

- Only 4 summons, so plays under nib.

- Exosisters can OTK turn 3.

- Argonauts burn for time.

- Budget

- If Exosisters or Argonauts get support, might synergise even better IDK.

 

cons: 

- Very weak end board.

- No turn 2 plays.

- Argonauts destroyed by spell/trap and monster destruction.

deck_name: Bystial Centur-Ion Yubel (Fusion x Synchro Festival 2025)
deck_description: This Centur-Ion deck focuses outgrinding the opponent and uses the Bystial and Yubel archetypes as support. Summon Centur-Ion Auxila to search for any Centur-Ion card, primarily Centur-Ion Phalanx, and use her End Phase effect to set up your future plays. Summon Centur-Ion Legatia on your opponent's turn to draw a card and potentially destroy one of their monsters with her effect. Phantom of Yubel provides a one-time monster negate. Nightmare Pain is an alternate win condition. Bystial Magnamhut and Bystial Druiswurm are super effective against light and dark decks. Branded Regained allows for some great grind game by reviving a Bystial monster if your opponent normal or special summons a monster and recycling, then drawing a card if a light or dark monster is banished.
A fun & easy to play zombie deck, combining Skull Servant with a classic zombie pile structure. Made to be played by beginners.

deck_name: Red Dragon Archfiend (Masterduel) (Fusion x Synchro Festival 2025)
deck_excerpt: "LET'S KICK THIS DUEL FESTIVAL INTO OVERDRIVE!"
deck_description:
We finally have 2025's dedicated Synchro and Fusion festival??? As Jack Atlas would says... "LET'S KICK THIS DUEL FESTIVAL INTO OVERDRIVE!"

Despite the relatively high power levels of the decks in the festival since Azamina, White Forest and Branded are running around, Red Dragon Archfiend carves a niche for itself. The deck can field the ENTIRE Bystial package, including 10 Bystial handtraps! Bystials simultaneously act as combo pieces for the deck, and hardcounters most of the current meta decks to banish their key GY light/dark monsters. On top of that, the deck maxes out on Nibiru and Droll, which stops many combo-centric strategies rampant in the festival. Based on my personal experience piloting Red Dragon Archfiend in the festival, it has been excellent! The perfect lineup of 16 anti-meta handtraps and the inherent consistency and power of Red Dragon has enabled an easy and fun festival for me. Hopefully it's the same for you! SHOW YOUR FESTIVAL OPPONENTS THE MEANING OF ABSOLUTE POWERFORCE!

If you want a more detailed guide on how to pilot this deck, please check out my earlier article on Red Dragon Archfiend from last year.

GLHF Duelists!

ACTIVATE: (Once/Turn): Target 1 of your banished Fiend monsters with 0 ATK/DEF. Lose LP equal to that card's Level x 100, then Special Summon it in Attack Mode to your side of the field.

deck_excerpt: So, Dragon Link is legal in this event?
deck_description:
For Legend Anthology, I wanted to play something different and fun, but that had a decent chance against Millennium (by far the most popular deck as you might be aware). This is what I've come up with. Please note that I've never played Rokkets or Dragon Link before, so I'm not sure how optimal the decklist is (it's just an event though, doesn't need to be perfect).

This deck has a lot of gas and it's very fun to play (plus it's somewhat cheap). Your main goal is to setup Borrelend Dragon + Borreload Savage Dragon on your first turn, which against Millennium is just an auto win (especially the loaner, which has zero outs when going second) - you just wait for the opponent to summon the Exodia Incarnate and then you negate it.

To achieve this, we need to do a lot of special summoning and link climbing, which the Rokkets (Rokket Tracer in particular), aided by cards like Absorouter Dragon, Noctovision Dragon, Quick Launch, Borrel Regenerator, Boot Sector Launch, Dillingerous Dragon, etc. are very good at doing.

In addition to all this, there's also a small Fusion package in there, accessible by Rapid Trigger (searchable by Double Disruptor Dragon) or Dark End Evaporation Dragon. It is not bad going first, but becomes especially useful when going second, since all the 3 fusions I'm playing have effects to destroy opponent's cards (now that I think about it, it would be funny to try out Dragon's Mirror in this deck...)

The biggest threats to this deck are cards like Ultimate Slayer or Santa Claws, which can deal with Borrelend and are unable to be negated with Borreload Savage. The loaners don't have those though. When going second, Heart of the Blue-Eyes is also extremely annoying, since it's GY effect outs any of our boss monsters.

There are more cards that you can potentially play in here to improve the power of the deck even more, such as Chaos Dragon Levianeer and the other Borrel Link monsters, but those are all URs that I didn't want to craft. I also wanted to try out more copies of Ultimate Slayer, but I only own one at the moment.

All in all, a very fun and somewhat underrated deck in the event, considering the power level of everything else that's available. I know most people disliked this event, but with some creativity you can definitely enjoy it.

In the attached video you can watch some amazing duels and have an idea of how the deck functions. As alawys, I appreciate your thoughts. I hope you enjoy it!

deck_excerpt: The maiden's prayers have been answered!
deck_description:
The Invoked archetype has some great synergy with the Blue-Eyes archetype thanks to the release of Spirit with Eyes of Blue! Aleister the Invoker is now a bridge to a Blue-Eyes White Dragon because Spirit with Eyes of Blue can use him as link material.

The Standard Blue-Eyes Invoked Play

Only requires Aleister the Invoker!

1. Normal summon Aleister the Invoker.

2. Activate his effect to search for Invocation.

3. Link summon Spirit with Eyes of Blue by sending Aleister as link material.

4. Activate Spirit with Eyes of Blue's effect to search for Mausoleum of White. 

5. Activate Mausoleum of White.

6. Activate Mausoleum of White's effect to send a Blue-Eyes White Dragon from your hand or deck to the graveyard and boost Spirit with Eyes of Blue's attack.

7. Activate Spirit with Eyes of Blue's effect to tribute itself to revive the Blue Eyes White Dragon in your graveyard. This will free you from Spirit with Eyes of Blue's dragon lock.

8. Activate Invocation to banish Aleister and Spirit with Eyes of Blue from your graveyard to summon Invoked Mechaba.

9. Activate Invocation's graveyard effect to add Aleister from your banished zone back to your hand.

From here you can start your Blue-Eyes plays without the fear of Nibiru, the Primal Being courtesy of Invoked Mechaba's protection. Mausoleum of White grants you an additional normal summon of a level 1 light tuner, so you can normal summon a tuner like Effect Veiler to synchro summon Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon with the Blue-Eyes White Dragon on your field.

deck_excerpt: the true king is back from banned
deck_description:
The Tyranny of Master Peace, the True Dracoslayer King

In the age of dragons and war, when the sky was torn asunder by wings of fire and the land quaked beneath the march of tyrants, there rose a warrior whose name would be whispered in awe and fear alike.

He was once but a man, a noble knight of the Dracoslayers, sworn to purge the darkness that lurked in the hearts of dragons and their wicked kin. Clad in sacred armor and wielding the might of the divine, he waged war against the Dracoverlords, those who sought dominion through the will of their corrupted beasts. Steel clashed against fang, light against shadow, and for a time, balance held.

Yet the world is cruel, and war spares no hero.

The earth trembled, and from its shattered depths emerged the True Kings—primordial forces of destruction, neither dragon nor mortal, but something far greater. Their power twisted the land itself, bending creation to their will. The Dracoverlords, once mighty, fell before them. The Dracoslayers, noble in purpose, found their blades dull against the weight of fate.

And in this twilight of hope, one knight made a choice.

He who had been a slayer of dragons offered himself unto the True Kings. He took their fire into his soul, their power into his veins, and was reborn not as a man, but as a god among mortals. No longer did he stand beside the Dracoslayers, nor did he kneel before the Dracoverlords. He had ascended beyond them all.

Thus was Master Peace, the True Dracoslayer King, born into legend.

No blade could touch him, no spell could bind him, no force of man nor beast could defy his will. With the power of the True Dracos, he forged a kingdom where none could stand against him. What he declared law became reality; what he willed into being was so.

He did not rule with cruelty, nor did he seek destruction—he sought only order. But order under an immortal king is but a gilded cage, and the world does not suffer the reign of one who cannot fall.

And so, the storm came.

Those who still drew breath beneath his shadow rose against him, wielding weapons forged in desperation, spells woven from defiance. His kingdom trembled as war ignited once more. The people, the mages, the warriors—all struck at the throne of their undying ruler.

And then, on that fateful day, in a battle that shook the heavens, the impossible came to pass.

Master Peace fell.

How? None could say. Did his own power consume him? Did the remnants of the Dracoslayers find a way to sever his divine strength? Or did the world itself reject a king who could never die?

His armor lay shattered, his blade broken, his rule ended. His name was erased from history, his power sealed beyond reach. No longer would his presence bend reality, no longer would his will shape destiny.

And yet…

The wind still whispers his name. The embers of war still glow faintly in the darkness. And some say that if ever the world should fall into chaos once more, if ever the Dracoslayers or the Draconic scourge should rise again—

Then so too shall Master Peace, the True Dracoslayer King.

For a king may fall, but a legend never dies.

 
4o

deck_excerpt: Wield the power of the mightiest dragons!
deck_description: Spirit with Eyes of Blue + Mausoleum of White can convert an Effect Veiler or a negated Centur-Ion Primera into a Blue-Eyes White Dragon. Neo Kaiser Sea Horse is great because he's a light level 4 tuner that can special summon himself from your hand if you control a Blue-Eyes White Dragon, so you can easily make Centur-Ion Auxila to go into your Centur-Ion combos then banish him from your graveyard to summon a Bystial. Activate Neo Kaiser's graveyard effect to send Maiden of White from your deck to your graveyard. Maiden can special summon herself from your graveyard if you special summoned a Blue-Eyes White Dragon, then you can send her from your field to your graveyard to place a True Light from your hand, deck, or graveyard face-up on your field or use her as synchro material for Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon. True Light allows for some awesome grind games because it can revive a Blue-Eyes White Dragon every turn and Centur-Ion Auxila protects it from card effect destruction. Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon is a strong boss monster that can negate graveyard effects and tribute itself to summon a light dragon synchro from your extra deck, such as Crimson Dragon or Blue-Eyes Ultimate Spirit Dragon. Blue-Eyes Ultimate Spirit Dragon is an even stronger boss monster that can negate any card on the field to gain an extra 1000 attack for the turn and it can revive a Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon from your graveyard if it is destroyed by battle or card effect.

deck_name: Lord of D's Guide to Blue-Eyes Primite (February 2025)
deck_excerpt: Blue-Eyes is unironically meta viable thanks to the White Destiny Structure Deck!
deck_description:
Yugioh's favourite iconic monster, Blue-Eyes White Dragon, gets a complete overhaul and power-up with the TCG release of the Structure Deck: Blue-Eyes White Destiny! You get to now unironically play Blue-Eyes competitively, going toe-to-toe with meta heavyweights like Ryzeal, Maliss and Fiendsmith! Kaiba certainly rigged this structure deck to be as powerful and busted as possible so his beloved Kisara can obliterate duelists with her burst stream of destruction!
 
While Blue-Eyes can pretty much summon monsters with every Extra Deck type (except Pendulum, since Konami hates Pendulum), the strategy revolves on summoning mostly Synchro monsters, like Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon, Blue-Eyes Ultimate Spirit Dragon, Crimson Dragon, and Cosmic Blazar Dragon. This synchro combo line gives Blue-Eyes multiple negates per turn, gigantic dragon boss monsters and resource recursion for follow-up next turn. The Primite engine also adds an extra layer of consistency and power to Blue-Eyes giving more starters, extension and an additional negate as well! 
 
The incredible amount of consistency that the new structure deck grants also allows the deck to have about 20 staples, offering a perfect balance of starters and handtraps to so that the strategy remains viable going first and second! Kaiba and his dragon darling Kisara certainly now have their place in the 2025 Yugioh meta, so I think it's about time to make a video and guide to be the best Blue-Eyes duelist!
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
Blue-Eyes Primite is composed of 2 archetypes which all lead to basically the same endboard. The deck is also consistent enough to maindeck 18 staples! Since any level 4 or lower spellcaster or dragon monster can link away to Spirit with Eyes of Blue, the this deck has 18 1-card starters which ends on a full Blue-Eyes board. 

The BLUE-EYES cards are minimalistic relative to earlier Blue-Eyes decklists due to the new cards introduced in the structure deck. It is composed of a mere 16 cards. The Blue-Eyes deck core is composed of x3 Maiden of White, x3 Sage of Eyes of Blue, x3 Wishes for Eyes of Blue, x1 Roar of the Blue-Eyes Dragons, x1 White Mausoleum, x1 True Light, x1 Ultimate Fusion, x1 Majesty with Dragons of White and of course, x2 of the original Blue-Eyes White Dragon. 
 
A PRIMITE cards count as extra starters and extenders for the Blue-Eyes strategy, and grants it an additional omni-negate. It is composed of x3 Lordly Lode, x3 Ether Beryl and x1 Drillbeam. 
 
This decklist has 18 STAPLE cards, due to the extreme consistency the link-1 and new support cards offer. The best handtraps for the current meta are included, which are x3 Effect Veiler (doubles as 1-card starter), x3 Imperm, x2 Nibiru, x2 Droll, x3 Ash, x3 Dominus Purge and x1 Bystial Magnamhut. The last staple is a non-handtrap, which is x1 Called By due to the prevalence of handtraps this format. 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
Blue-Eyes has a relatively simple and straightforward gameplan - summoning big synchro boss monsters to negate your opponent's plays, then OTK next turn with overwhelming firepower and resources. This is done by going for a linear comboline, until massive Blue-Eyes/Crimson Dragon boss monsters like Ultimate Spirit and Blazar are deployed. If the Primite engine is accessible, an additional omni-negate is accessible via Drillbeam. 
 
Here is the standard opening combo for Blue-Eyes: 
 
Sage with Eyes of Blue + Primite Ether Beryl + any 1 card = Blue-Eyes Ultimate Spirit Dragon (omni-negate), Primite Drillbeam (omni-negate banish), Stardust Sifr Dragon (monster negate and destroy) (destruction protection), Neos Blue-Eyes Ultimate Dragon (targeting protection), follow-up (True Light, Lordly Lode, Ether Beryl, Drillbeam all recur). 
  1. Normal summon Ether Beryl. Activate Ether Beryl's on-summon effect to set Lordly Lode from deck.
  2. Activate Lordly Lord to add from deck Drillbeam. 
  3. Link summon Spirit with Eyes of Blue using Ether Beryl. Activate Spirit with Eyes of Blue's on-summon effect to search for Mausoleum of White from deck. 
  4. Activate Mausoleum of White. Activate the effect of Mausoleum of White to normal summon Sage with Eyes of White. 
  5. Activate Sage's on-summon effect to search for Maiden of White from deck. 
  6. Discard Maiden of White to place on your field True Light from deck. 
  7. Activate Mausoleum of White targeting Spirit with Eyes of Blue and send from deck to GY Blue-Eyes White Dragon. 
  8. Tribute Spirit with Eyes of Blue to summon from the GY Blue Eyes White Dragon. 
  9. Activate Maiden of White's effect in the GY to summon herself since Blue-Eyes White Dragon was summoned on the field. 
  10. Synchro summon Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon using Blue Eyes + Sage of Eyes of Blue. 
  11. Activate True Light to set from deck Wishes for Eyes of Blue. 
  12. Activate Wishes for Eyes of Blue discarding 1 card to add from deck Roar of the Blue Eyed White Dragons and Effect Veiler (that's right this handtrap is searchable!) (If you already have Roar, search instead for Majesty). 
  13. Activate Roar of the Blue Eyed White Dragons to summon from deck Blue-Eyes White Dragon.
  14. Banish Wishes for Eyes of Blue from the GY to equip to Blue-Eyes a Neo Blue-Eyes Ultimate Dragon from your Extra Deck. (Neos Blue-Eyes Ultimate is targeting protection). 
  15. Synchro summon a second Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon using Blue Eyes + Maiden of White. 
  16. Tribute Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon to summon from your Extra Deck Blue-Eyes Ultimate Spirit Dragon.
  17. Tribute your second Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon to summon from your Extra Deck Crimson Dragon. 
  18. Activate Crimson Dragon targeting Blue-Eyes Ultimate Spirit Dragon to summon from Extra Deck Stardust Sifr Divine Dragon. (This prevents your Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon from being destroyed by Spirit Dragon's effect during the End Phase). 
  19. Activate Lordly Lode declaring Blue-Eyes White Dragon to summon it from the GY.
  20. Set the rest of your cards, especially Primite Drillbeam.  
If you only have Ether Beryl, the strategy still ends on an omni-negate, bounce and follow-up. 

Primite Ether Beryl = Hieratic Seals (bounce and summon any Dragon from deck) + Primite Drillbeam (omni-negate banish)
  1. Normal summon Ether Beryl. Activate Ether Beryl's on-summon effect to set Lordly Lode from deck.
  2. Activate Lordly Lord to add from deck Drillbeam. 
  3. Link summon Spirit with Eyes of Blue using Ether Beryl. Activate Spirit with Eyes of Blue's on-summon effect to search for Mausoleum of White from deck. 
  4. Activate Lordly Lode declaring Blue-Eyes White Dragon to summon it from deck. 
  5. Link summon Hieratic Seals of the Heavenly Spheres using Blue-Eyes White Dragon + Spirit with Eyes of Blue. 
  6. During your opponent's turn, return your opponent's face-up card to their hand with Hieratic Seals and summon Blue-Eyes from deck. Since Blue-Eyes on board, you can use Drillbeam to negate your opponent's effects since you control a normal monster. 
Going first, you make powerful board with multilayered interruption and with plenty of follow-up next turn. Blue-Eyes Ultimate Spirit Dragon, Cosmic Blazar Dragon and Primite Drillbeam give this deck triple omni-negates per turn! Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon also acts as a minor floodgate and can negate a GY card activation. This deck can make this board through 1-2 cards, so your hand is likely full of one of the 17 handtraps the strategy uses to further stop your opponent!
 
Going second, you weaken your opponent with the 18 handtraps/staples you have. Then your Blue-Eyes cards have enough gas to bait enough interruption, generate enough resources and gigantic dragons to push through your opponent's board! It's notable that Blue-Eyes Tyrant Dragon can attack every monster your opponent controls and it's easily accessible in this strategy through Wishes for Eyes of Blue. 

GENERAL TIPS
  • If you get "Shifter'd," you can still play the game competently. Set-up your Primite omni-negate, and if you have an extender, you can link summon Hieratic Seals for a bounce. You also have handtraps to use as well!
  • Activate your Primite cards first to bait handtraps/interruptions, and then you can go for the full Blue-Eyes combo. 
  • Blue-Eyes Tyrant Dragon can attack every monster on your opponent's board, effectively resetting their field! This boss monster is easily summonable as part of your Blue-Eyes combo, so keep this in mind when you give your opponent a counter attack on turns 2/3! 
  • Handtraps that really harm Blue-Eyes are Droll (you search and add a ton from deck), Nibiru (No way to play through it), and Bystials (banish your Maiden of White/Blue-Eyes from the GY). Watch out for these cards, and perhaps it's good to run x3 Crossout Designators during handtrap heavy formats! 
  • Your big choke point for this strategy is "Wishes for Eyes of Blue." It discards one of your cards to add two cards from deck, so if this gets negates, you'll end up with a -2 in card advantage! 
  • A unique handtrap, Dominous Purge, is used in this strategy since Blue-Eyes and it's support are mostly light monsters. If you use its card effect in the hand, remember you cannot activate Dark, Water and Fire monster effects for the rest of the duel! That means you cannot use monsters like Ash Blossom and Magnamhut. 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
Looking at the new Blue-Eyes support, it seems that Kaiba Corp certainly has had a hand in making this incredible structure deck - Blue Eyes White Destiny! The extra consistency boosters like the link-1 Spirit with Eyes of Blue and the 2-for-1 searcher Wishes for Eyes of Blue make summoning your Blue-Eyes boss monsters an easy feat! Since Blue-Eyes won its last major event back in 2017, 2025 may be the year that the beloved iconic face of Duel Monsters, Blue Eyes, may win another championship! Will Blue-Eyes be able to catch up to the cut-throat TCG meta? Or will it just be another rogue deck compared to the heavyweights? Only individual duelist skill, powerful love for Kisara and timely tournament results will tell! 
 
GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: Blessed by the angel of stun!
deck_description:
This is an experimental Gladiator Beast build tailored with a wide arsenal of anti-meta cards.

Tech Cards

Gladiator Beasts rarely hit the graveyard, and they can be recycled by the effects of Gladiator Beast Darius and Gladiator Beast Equeste, so this deck can run Guardian Eatos to help defeat strong threats. Guardian Eatos can special summon herself from your hand if you have no monsters in your graveyard, and you can special summon multiple copies of her in a turn as long as her summoning condition is still met. This deck can also run Dimensional Fissure to keep monsters out of either player's graveyard.

Trap Stun negates the effects of all other traps on the field for a turn, so you can attack the opponent without worry! Trap Stun and Dark Bribe are super effective against discard traps like Raigeki Break, Karma Cut, and Phoenix Wing Wind Blast!

Mask of Restrict and Zombie World are hard counters against Frog, Monarch, and Plant decks. Mask of Restrict prevents all forms of tributing, so it renders Enemy Controller, Tytannial, Princess of Camellias, and Super Solar Nutrient useless and prevents Caius the Shadow Monarch and Gigaplant from being tribute summoned. Zombie World prevents tribute summoning as well, unless it's for the uncommon zombie monsters, but more importantly, it disrupts most type-based strategies by transforming all monsters on the field and in either player's graveyards into zombies.

Ancient Forest is a unique floodgate that prevents flip monster effects, such as from the popular Ryko, Lightsworn Hunter, Gravekeeper's Spy, and Super-Nimble Mega Hamster. Also, it destroys monsters that have attacked at the end of the battle phase, but the Gladiator Beasts can avoid this effect by tagging out before it resolves.

Swords of Concealing Light can break established boards with ease by flipping your opponent's monsters face-down. It's great against combo heavy decks that don't typically play a lot of backrow, such as Plants, Dragons, and Lightsworn.

deck_excerpt: Build into a devastating board of Colossus and Rank 8 Negates, then finish your opponent off by linking into Accesscode for the final blow.
deck_description:
UPDATED FOR FEB 2025 (Rogue Non-Meta)

Okay, so what am I trying to do?
This deck is a Thunder Dragon 8-Axis lockdown deck that focuses on getting out Colossus as fast as possible, using Armaggeddon Knight as your main starter.


 

Armaggeddon will send any DARK monster from your deck to your grave, letting you get Thunder Dragons in your grave, as well as Bystials. I highly reccomend sending "Thunder Dragonroar" or "Bystial Saronir" since Dragondark can send himself recursively, and Saronir can send a Bystial down with it.

Your stage 1 end board will consist of multiple "negates" (I use this term loosely, as Dingirsu doesn't actually "negate", per say) with Dingirsu and/or Titanic long name, and preferrably Colossus to prevent searches. The main way to get into Rank 8s is with Horus, as well as Bystials. You mainly want to get all four Horus members in your GY to Special, as you will be able to XYZ twice. You can then go into "The Zombie Vampire" if you choose to do so, and mill four cards, as well as get another Special. Just make sure you have Dingirsu or another good negation tool to prevent your opponent from stopping the combo. After you pull off this combo, you can do damage, or advance to stage 2. Your stage 2 end board, and your last combos, would be making "Knightmare Unicorn" (or another rank 3), then linking into "Accesscode Talker", activating its effect, and dealing massive damage with 5300 ATK, ending the duel with a quick victory.

Side Deck
Included in the Side Deck are some more handtraps and disruptions, such as Nibiru, Veiler, and Shifter, which this deck has no issues playing under.

deck_description: Traptantalizing Tune serves as draw power in the event Infinite Impermanence or Evenly Matched will not be helpful, while also allowing you to send World Legacy Mind Meld to the Graveyard for later. Additionally, it can be banished to allow you to reuse Mind Meld to summon monsters to the zones your Link Monsters point to. Pot of the Forbidden serves as a much needed wall that can be easily summoned with Master of Ham, while also granting more draw power and disruption. Its effect can be activated early and repeatedly with World Legacy Pawns.

deck_description: Largely revolving around Dark Beckoning Beast and Opening of the Spirit Gates for combos, the deck can almost always get the Sacred Beasts out first turn, usually with Fallen Paradise up as well. Every turn Fallen Paradise is not destroyed you get to draw two more cards, either of which could negate your opponent's next move or allow you to summon another Sacred Beast. Eventually you'll overwhelm the opponent and you even have the option to clear their board with Armityle the Chaos Phantom - Phantom of Fury.

deck_excerpt: Summon Raviel turn one and double its attack to 8000.
deck_description: The deck focuses mainly on "tribute" effects. Raviel tributing a monster, Darkest Diabolos summoning itself if a tribute occurs, Chaos Summoning Beast and Dark Summoning Beast tributing themselves, etcetera, allow you to summon tokens each end phase. These tokens can be used on your opponent's turn with I:P Masquerena to summon more threatening things such as Unchained Abomination. These effects can now use your opponent's monsters to activate their effects as opposed to your own with Lair of Darkness. Meaning you can tribute your opponent's boss monster with Raviel to increase its attack, then double that with Raviel, Lord of Phantasms - Shimmering Scraper, and attack for colossal damage. Salamangreat Almiraj and Fallen Paradise provide protection when attacking.

Wanna explore what Harpies can do? Noobies and players with unfinished competitive decks will have a good deal of trouble when fighting the strategy pool of a pure harpie deck. 

Due to how most of the resources are situational (if your opponent keeps cards in their spell/trap zone, if their monsters are vanilla, immune to target or beatdown), it's highly advisable to exchange between deck and side deck cards).

Since most of your resources are searchable and be recycled, the thicker deck pile will not be a particular problem.

deck_excerpt: This is an update to my Ice Barrier Deck for Nov. 2024 TCG Format. I hope you enjoy it.
deck_description:
The updates to the deck consist of the following :

 

+1 Strategist of the Ice Barrier

  • Combo this with Revealer in Graveyard and its Draw Effect is godly. Not to mention that Strategist is a Spellcaster which means Secret Village of the Spellcasters paired with this card becomes problematic for the opponent.

 

+1 Defender of the Ice Barrier

  • Not gonna lie, but having this card is a must. This and Icejade Gymir along with Lancea to bring out Georgius which Summons this card makes an impenetrable Ice Barrier.

 

+3 Swap Frog

  • Why did I not run this card earlier?! To anyone who wants to play Ice Barrier; You MUST run this card at maximum! This card is a free Summon which pitches Mirror Mage either by discarding from hand to Special Summon this card or sending from Deck to Graveyard. When Mirror Mage hits the Graveyard; you get a search for an Ice Barrier card.

 

+1 Monster Reborn

  • Great Extender as well as a Reviver card for bring back a powerful monster previously destroyed.

 

+1 Secret Village of the Spellcasters

  • Since some  Ice Barrier monsters are Spellcaster type; this card can be devastating for the opponent. This is better than Warlock because Warlock can easily be run over by a monster under 1600 ATK should Defender be out on the field and Secret Village is way better than Spellbreaker because she makes you go -1 in card advantage and her effect is not a Quick Effect; which means if you summon this card via via Lancea or Georgius during the opponent’s turn; you cannot lock them out of Spell Cards.

 

+1 Gozen Match

  • Every Monster on your field will 100% be WATER. You will be unaffected by its effects while your opponent suffers massive disadvantage.

 

+1 White Aura Whale

  • Decent Nuke as well as Piercing Damage Monster. Also it can revive itself.

 

———

 

-1 Zuijin of the Ice Barrier 

  • There are cards that do a better job than what this card does.

 

-3 Shared Ride

  • After experimenting with this card; I found myself to be bricking more than reaping its benefits. It is an alternative to Max “C”/Mulcharmy Package albeit a Not-So-Good variant, but cheap nonetheless.

 

-1 Crossout Designator 

  • I found myself to be bricking more at multiple copies.

 

-3 Ice Barrier

  • A good card: Great Battle Trap, Excellent generic WATER searcher. I wanted to run at 1 for Gameciel combo, but I couldn’t make room for it in a 40 card Main Deck.

 

-1 Bahamut Shark 

  • With Swap Frog in this Deck List; It is not needed as Bahamut Shark’s only purpose is to summon Toadally Awesome. Swap Frog with Mirror Mage is a direct access to Toadally Awesome.

deck_excerpt: Hardcounter the Fiendsmith, Azamina, White Forest, Snake-Eyes and Yubel piles with mass Bystials, handtraps and mecha pilots!
deck_description:
For all the frustrations on Masterduel ladder right now with it's "spashable engine" "multiple negates" "10 minute combo" nonsense with Fiendsmith, Azamina, White Forest, Snake-Eyes and Yubel piles, I have one outlet which makes the game fun again - Bystials. Bystials counter the GY dependent strategies listed above, and any deck that can field them with a critical mass of handtraps is effectively playable on Masterduel ladder! Centur-Ion is one such deck, being hyper-consistent with 14 one-card starters. This means that these mecha pilots can fight alongside their arsenal of 20 handtraps, allowing them to go toe-to-toe with those annoying pile powerhouses such as White Forest, Fiendsmith and Snake-Eyes that plague the game right now!

deck_excerpt: What I have at the moment for my Blue Eyes Deck
deck_description: Effectivly the contents of the Kaiba deck from "Legendary Decks II" and the "Blue-Eyes White Destiny" Structure Deck, with a few odds and ends.

About the best version of "pure" Digital Bug you can get (true pure, without the Beetroopers/Spiders and the like is really bad)
Explanation of Spider engine:
Hand: (Mother Spider)
Endboard: (Varudras, with potential Cicada King)
Summon Mother, eff to summon 3 Babies, Baby eff tribute a Baby to make the 2 remaining Babies lvl 10, make Varudras.
If you have any lvl 3 in hand you can use Baby's gy eff to detach from Varudras and summon itself, then NS the 3 and make Cicada King.

Samurai Beetle is in the side deck for a Runick/Banish-centric deck that might banish your cards.
Ultimate Slayer is there, although hard to side in due to the tight Extra Deck.
Book of Eclipse is in the main because it is so good in combination with this deck, Book everything then on the next turn Frozen Lady to wipe everything
Frozen Lady is a card I've always wanted to use, and now it's probably one of this decks best cards. You can slap it on top of Corebage, then slap Lancer on top of that after using it's effect to potentially wipe the field.
Two Zeus is suprisingly mandatory, that and Varudras are about the only ways this deck can even have a chance to win.

With enough practice and skill (I have practice, just not skill) you can win against some good decks on occasion

Another thing to note is that, even though Lady, Eclipse, and Zeus are all going second cards, you still want to go first so you can set up a Cicada King, Scale Bomber, and/or Rhinosebus.

deck_description: You can fairly consistently summon powerful link monsters if nothing else. Use Duza to pitch another Unification, use I:P Masquerena and Duza to summon either Triple Burst Dragon or Scareclaw Tri-Heart, use Unification again, summon Duza, pitch Cubic Karma, and then summon Accesscode Talker. Accesscode can then gain the attack of the strongest link monster you used, and banish the rest of them to destroy your opponent's backrow.

While your opponent is playing checkers, you will be playing chess.  This is less of an analogy and more of a literal transcription of how you're making this world a worse place with these cards in your hand.  Thankfully more people in the fall of 2022 wanted to play the Right Way and went with Labrynth and Runick, so we were spared a Tactical Masters trifecta.  

Strategy is the same: get big cards on field, clear opponent field, and swing to win.  It's a basic strategy, but we found a new way to do it that takes far too long.  Place your pendulums and if the conditions are right you can summon them to the field.  Sometimes they move other cards.  Sometimes when they move something happens.  Okay.
This list allows you to play in turn zero

deck_excerpt: Thanks to the new Blue-Eyes Structure Deck, the "Buster Lock" is easier than ever to achieve!
deck_description:
Konami's incredible support for Blue-Eyes with the White Destiny Structure Deckhas benefitted other strategies accidentally since level 1 light tuners have become so searchable. A strategy with that centres around a level 1 light tuner turns out to be Buster Blader! Buster Whelp of the Destruction Sword is a level 1 light tuner, made searchable by Sage of Eyes of Blue, and by extension, by the new card from White Destiny, Wishes of Eyes of Blue! Combined with the double normal summon for light level 1s from Mausoleum of White, the "Buster Lock" where every card your opponent controls turns into a dragon, made to go to defense position, and cannot activate any effects is much easier to achieve! Instead of using the very expensive (currently about $350 USD) Primite engine, the Buster blade engine of 7 cards is a cheaper but just as powerful alternative! Not only that, Buster Blader is one of Yugi's nostalgic ace cards, so you get some extra cool factor when buster locking your unfortunate opponent with Yugioh's DRAGONSLAYER! 

If you want a detailed guide on how to play Blue-Eyes, click here!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

deck_excerpt: Yu-Gi-Oh! Minor Arcana For A Yu-Gi-Oh! Tarot
deck_description:
This is my Yu-Gi-Oh! minor arcana!

Yu-Gi-Oh! has 2 archetypes based on the major arcana, and *some* cards based on standard playing card suits, but there isn't a set of cards based on the traditional 52 deck of cards, let alone the minor arcana's 56 cards. But instead of buying a tarot deck with little to no meaning to me, I was determined to make one of my own :) Here's how it works:

Suits:
The traditional tarot suits are all related to the 4 base alchemical elements of Earth, Water, Fire, and Air. Luckily, Yu-Gi-Oh! (mostly) uses all of those elements on the cards themselves as Attributes. In this deck, the Earth monsters are the suit of Pentacles, the Water monsters are the suit of Cups, the Fire monsters are the suit of Wands, and the Wind monsters are the Air suit of Swords. 

Ranks:
The traditional tarot ranks are very similar to the standard "1 through 10, Jack, King, and Queen" values used for playing cards, but the tarot uses one additional court (face) card called the Page, and the Jacks are instead known as the Knights. These court cards are represented by the True Kings for the Kings, assorted queens for the Queens, the elemental knights as the Knights, and the Prank Kids as the Pages. The remaining cards have their ranks represented by their level. The numerical ranks 6-10 are represented by royally-named Yu-Gi-Oh! archetypes like the Monarchs that represent 6s, or Time Lords that represent 10s. The numerical ranks 1-5 are represented by the Ghost Sisters, a few random normal monsters I liked, and, in the interest of respecting the witch-y spellcaster-y concept of the tarot, the evolutions of the Charmer Familiars (ranks 5, 4, most of 2, and gigabyte as an Ace). 

This decklist is sorted by rank, then suit to make the theming easier to see. Feel free to play around with this and add your own cards to make a tarot of your own ^-^

Resources:

  • Minor Tarot Guide: https://www.tarot.com/tarot/meaning-of-numbers-in-minor-arcana
  • My Major Arcana List:

People discovering the sheer value The Dark - Hex Sealed Fusion brings to the Millennium deck as a way to cheat out Millennium-Eyes Restrict permanantly can't be overstated, but in all other builds you're too reliant on hard drawing it. Millennium is one of the best archetypes to play Small World in because every main deck monster acts as a bridge to each other, and they also happen to be the perfect bridge to The Dark.

Off of any Millennium monster in hand except for Maiden and Blue-Eyes, you can bridge into The Dark. You can also use Small World to bridge out of non-engine into engine using the ghost girls, both being level 3 allowing you to bridge from The Dark into Golem, who are both Rock. Since an ideal Millennium Endboard looks like Exodia, Restrict, and Exxod and Azurune in back row, it's perfectly fine to sacrifice engine at the cost of making sure you have that perfect board.

Your goal is to get at least two millennium monsters on board to Link into Silhouhatte, then to Normal Summon The Dark to make Restrict by Tributing The Dark and Rabbit, allowing you to finish up your turn by making Exodia.

The one problem with this new build is you can easily fall prey to Nib with zero counter. Restrict is a very good monster negate, but it can't do anything about hand traps that resolve in hand. Once Nib hits the field, Restrict and Exodia will both be gone.

deck_excerpt: Staying true to my word here is my White Forest list for SUDA!!!!!!
deck_description: Silly deck that I'm try Harding to get my invite to nats in July.
First draft of a crystal beast pile, heavily inspired by The Crystal Beast Guy

and experimental deck that I came up with, utelising the graveyard heavily by combining engines that are generic enough and all synergize with eachother well to work together and send a bunch of cards from both players decks to their graveyard. This deck majorly loses to dimension shifter so to compensate almost every shifter answer is included + a bunch of handtraps and non-engine that kill banishment decks like Maliss and Flowandereez. This deck is extremely flexible but relies on good mills to keep extending into generic xyz and link monsters like Varudras, and Yuki-ona for interruption, and psychic end and Number 35 to close out games with their incredible synergy with Rollback's life point cost. other good forms of interruption include Dies Ire and the eldlich trap monsters + an eldlich name on field (which is easy to pump out with sanguine in grave most of the time). another card I was considering was dragons mind which pairs very well with the eldlich engine and this deck's tendency to dump a bunch of traps to the grave it can set itself very easily. both eldlich engine and fiendsmith engine can also pump out either full power chaos angel or half power chaos angel by utelising the lvl5 token delta of invitation spawns. if you do not have chaos angel however it is not mandatory and sillouhatte rabbit can suffice as more trap monster leaning. The main endboard wants either varudras or Yuki-ona + Dias Ire for either an omni negate or Yuki-ona's (not once per tern) face up negate every time a monster is summoned from the graveyard which works on sanguine, Lacrima's grave effect, or your opponent summoning from grave. This deck has limited handtrap space as it does with the nature of mill decks not wanting dead mills all of the time. I hope you enjoy what I've cooked and feel free to give me any feedback!

deck_description: It's a decent deck for this event. Maintain your resources with Shining Angel, Dekoichi the Battlechanted Locomotive, and Gravekeeper's Spy until you're in a favorable offensive position. Black Luster Soldier - Envoy of the Beginning can easily win games. Spirit Reaper and Marshmallon are your best defenders because they can't be destroyed by battle. Royal Decree and Jinzo punish players that use too many traps. Limiter Removal is great for sneaky OTKs. The Dragon Cannons can theoretically break through stall decks and Dimension Fusion can recover resources from the banished zone, but these cards are rarely resolved in a meaningful way.

deck_excerpt: The graveyard couldn't hold them back!
deck_description: Spam the board with your undead hoard! Pyramid Turtle, Giant Rat, and Spirit Reaper maintain field presence! Vampire's Curse and Vampire Lord are your main boss monsters and they're easily searchable with Pyramid Turtle's effect. Goblin Zombie gets a mandatory search for Spirit Reaper, Curse of Vampire, or another Goblin Zombie if it's sent from the field to the graveyard by any means. Exiled Force and Injection Fairy Lily are searchable by Giant Rat's effect, and they take down threats your targeting spells can't normally deal with like Horus the Black Flame Dragon LV8 or King Dragun. Spell Shattering Arrow is theoretically good against the common face-up spells in the meta, such as Necrovalley, Snatch Steal, and Level Limit - Area B, but I haven't played a game where it had any impact yet.

deck_name: Stall Burn v1.0 [MD - Duel Trial/Time Travel 2004 2025]
Skill Drain Archfiends (Duel Trial - Time Travel 2004)
deck_description: It's a cool casual deck for this event. The Archfiends' high attack stats mow down most common normal summons. Pandemonium allows you to search for Desrook Archfiend when one of your Archfiends is destroyed by a card effect and sent to the graveyard, such as by Sakuretsu Armor, Tribe-Infecting Virus, and Lightning Vortex or even your own Torrential Tribute. Terrorking Archfiend is this deck's boss monster, and he can negate the effects of monsters he destroys in battle and even their graveyard effects are negated. Desrook Archfiend can discard itself to revive your Terrorking Archfiend from the graveyard when he's destroyed by any means, so you can get a little greedy with your plays. Skill Drain is quite effective against this monster effect heavy meta, and it doesn't negatively affect your monsters too much. Mystic Tomato and Newdoria are great defensive monsters that work under Skill Drain. Mystic Tomato can search for Newdoria when it's destroyed by battle and sent to the graveyard and Newdoria has a mandatory effect that targets and destroys a monster on the field when it's also destroyed by battle and sent to the graveyard.

deck_name: Dark Magician with Eyes of Blue
deck_excerpt: dark magician, spirit with eyes of blue, toy box,
I hate global warming. 200 IQ and you may have a chance to play this properly.
deck_description:
Plant is one of those 201 IQ decks that no one can play, but when they pretend they can, it can make a pretty board at a pretty fair price for Yu-Gi-Oh standards. So since no one can fathom the way to play this pile except for Sunseed Jess, here's the entire decklist and explanations:

MAIN:

3x Loci: The backbone of the deck and its main starter. The only vanilla monster that can turn into 7+ interruptions.

2x Twin: Twin is the definition of a "garnet", or a card you NEVER want to draw. So just in case you actually get unlucky enough you DO draw him, you have another one as a backup and the one in hand as a discard fodder for Blend.

3x Rosalina: Another one card combo starter. While she isn't nearly as good as a starter as Loci or Seed, she can get your combo going and is also a key extender in other combos.

1x Laurel: She is the one that actually starts your Jasmine shitshow and makes her such a warcrime enabler she is, ESPECIALLY in the Cactus Bouncer line.

1x Aromage Jasmine: Cactus line enabler.

3x Princess: She is a very important extender and a monster negate in the GY too. Also a free summon is never bad.

1x Mudan: A Konkon search and an another body for link summoning or tributing.

1x Snowdrop: The one that allows Teardrop to be summoned without losing your omni-negate (Regulus).

1x Petal: She searches for Snowdrop and is ANOTHER body for link climbing.

3x Lily: The decks most important extender. She not only searches for Regulus and enables his summon when in GY, but also lets you go into your 2nd Jasmine, which is crucial for this deck.

1x Regulus: An omni negate that is also hard to beat over when equipped with Lily. Very good.

3x Seed: Another card like Rosalina who is both a starter AND an extender. Easily one of the most important cards in the deck.

1x Beetle: Another garnet used for link summoning and further extending.

1x Cactus: The strongest card you can have on your endboard and one of the strongest floodgates to ever be printed into the game. Since he has 1800 ATK he's also hard to beat over with just a single normal summon.

1x Whip: Another brutal floodgate you can have that protects you from things such as Dark Ruler or Droplet. Also a part of you regular Loci combo in MD.

3x Blossom: Another card that is both a starter and an extender. Unlike the others, however, it is not a once per turn at all, so it can fulfil BOTH roles in the same combo.

3x Ash, 1x Nibiru and 2x Veiler: Pretty self-explanatory.

2x Sowing: Just like Twin, you do not want this in your opening hand, so play 2 as backup.

1x Blend: Used to both place Humid straight to S/T and banish from GY to summon Magnolia.

2x Konkon: Unlike others I play at 2, this one is not so catastrophical if you open it. You can side for just one.

1x Colloseum: Used to search Regulus in all the combos and also get banished by Rosemary in the Cactus Bouncer line.

Dai, One for One, Roar and Load: All are one card combo starter for your Loci combos.

3x Triple: A really good board breaker and also a response when getting hand trapped. You can side it out if you want.

1x Called by: The best anti-handtrap card you can ever have.

1x Crossout: The same as Called by, except you can also use it when you get Nibiru'd. You do have to have the same handtrap you want to stop in your deck, though.

1x Winds: Another extender that both adds Rosalina to your hand and also enables further Jasmine bullshittery. PRO TIP: ALWAYS chain Winds' second effect to the first, so you can chainblock itself from getting Ashed.

1x Sheet: One of many interruptions you can, and SHOULD have on your end board.

3x Imperm: Veiler on steroids.

EXTRA:

Dryas: The deck's second most important extra deck monster. Always play 2 in MD, since it allows for much stronger Loci combos.

Melias: I don't even know what it does. Just put another Dryas in MD instead of this thing.

Healer: Jasmine enabler. You can play 2 in MD, but it works perfectly even with only one.

Trasher: The substitute for the 2nd Healer.

3x Jasmine: If Loci is the backbone of this deck, Jasmine is its brain and heart. It is by far the most important card in the entire deck that allows for many, MANY war crimes and bullshittery to happen. Some people play only 2, but some combos utilize all 3, you should play them all.

Rosemary: Also a very important combo enabler. Just see the combos.

Soldier: Another extender in many combos, most notably the Loci and Seed ones.

Dancepione: Another extender. Her first effect is not very good and is RNG dependant, so don't use it. She allows for Strenna summon.

Resurgent: A good boss monster to have on your end board, since it's a free spin. Also who gave him his first name???

Magnolia: A very good protection, since it protects your Cactus board from things like Lightning Strom or Raigeki.

Teardrop: A free removal that is almost impossible to dodge, allowing you to get rid of strong bosses like Dragoon.

Strenna: Idk she does someting.

Beast: A free spell negate that also resets itself every turn. Very good.

NOTES AND TIPS:

I have Shifter in my side because this deck can actually play under it. Not very good, sure, but you can side it if you play against something like Tearlaments, Branded or any Fiendsmith variation.

With 20 one card starters on 60 cards, the chances of you drawing a one card starter in your opening hand are 33.3%, giving the deck insane consistency. Just pray that your opponent either didn't draw any handtraps or that you drew a Called by and/or Crossout.
Snake-eyes infernoids come together to make a powerful disruptive deck, one mathmech reanimate spell in the deck to fetch when your synchros die
