deck_description:
variation sourced from original IDGAF = horus into vanity's into ryzeals into board wipe into imagination

NB: replace numbers protection with new and improved "XYZ Unbreakable Barrier" for the better Astraltopia search card

likely one of my last theorycrafting decks to make, but this deck has been a blast and still is a blast to play imo. it feels like a culmination of all my posted, public decks (specifically) and i love that

there are a lot of processes behind it that can go either way depending on your hand— usually you would go horus or ryzeals or both (both is best) and vanity's still as a main focus

ranking up to C1000 goes from gimmick puppet fantasix (while using both effect card and xyz summoning mechanics listed in card text) all the way up to number 84: pain gainer from the other xyz rank cards. as long as you aren't negated or interrupted in any way shape or form, this is a guaranteed way to climb to C1000 Numerounius.

from C1000 Numerounius, if you drew ryzeals (bonfire helps search) or level 4 supports , you can consistently pressure opponent with both C1000 Numerounius and Dark Matter Demolition or Ryzeal Detonator. Dark Matter Demolition comes from Utopia Double into Dragonar into number card of choice (between 1 to 100). Dark Matter Demolition's "Cannot be destroyed by battle or card effects" works in synergy with Numerounius, where Numerounius continues to destroy and can ressurect your opponent's monsters, while Dark Matter Demolition can continue to attack due to it being unaffected by Numerounius' destruction effect. likewise, ryzeal detonator can also avoid destruction and pressure opponent alongside Numerounius (albeit costing material in the process), whereby: "If an Xyz Monster(s) you control would be destroyed by battle or card effect, you can detach 1 material from this card instead."
I play this, it's surely not perfect but I like it, it's fun. Also I hate Azamina...

deck_excerpt: How should we hardcounter "FTK boards" meta? BY NUKING THE HECK OUT OF IT WITH BOARDBREAKERS!
deck_description:
Masterduel's current meta is made up of the booooooooring combo piles that take 10 minute turns to poop out all their resources in their hand, deck and extra deck into the board and GY to create a nigh-invincible castle of multi-layered negates, pops and interruptions. 

How should we hardcounter it? BY NUKING THE EVERLIVING HECK OUT OF THEIR BOARDS!  

Evenly Matched? ✔️ Lightning Storm? ✔️ Raigeki? ✔️ Harpie's Feather Duster? ✔️ Triple Tactics Talent? ✔️ Sky Striker Arsenal? ✔️ 

In the hands of an inexperienced duelist, Sky Striker is fragile and it's often hardpressed to catch up to the speed of combo decks like White Forest, Fiendsmith, Yubel and Snake-Eye, so it's definitely up the skill of the individual pilot to bring out the full potential of Raye! Sky Striker is the ultimate challenge for duelists looking for a deck that is hard to master but it handsomely rewards skill and experience. The idea behind Blind Second Sky Strikers is to wipe out most if not all of your opponent's resources that they slap down on the board going first, and then close out the match with Sky Striker's grind game. Everyone in the opponent on ladder is slapping down their entire extra deck and main deck and hand into the board going first and you'll just wipe all that away with your ~20ish boardbreakers!  

To end off, I'd like to quote the words of a legendary duelist and #2 Sky Striker fan (I'm #1 lol): "Oh my Gosh, yes. I love Raye. I would die for Sky Striker Ace Raye. This support card is going to change my life and it's going to be the best card ever." ~ Joshua Schmidt

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: Maliss Deck with Bystials for post Supreme Darkness
deck_description: Well, here we are again, with the shifting focus of how people have been building Maliss at the top levels, i felt i should provide an update before ALIN releases the new support and @ignisters.  The big changes is the greater focus on bystials rather than other engines like Kashtira or Striker and the removal of Dotscaper.  losing the secondary engines arguably lowers the deck's floor slightly, though the removal of Dotscaper reduces the number of bricky hands, by giving less options for Lancea/Chaos Hunter turns and certianly lowers the ceiling since the big explosive turns don't come as easily without them or Dotscaper.  The benefit is more room for non-engine/handtraps and Allure for better consistency.  This list fits 18 handtraps including 6 Bystials, 3 board breakers and called by in the main as well as 2 allures in 40 cards.  There are no Fuwaloses here since i sold mine, but they would replace the Veilers if you have them.  Chaos Hunter is popping up more having Talents as a Thrust target and Knightmare Cerberus in extra provide answers to it along with Droplets.  Without Dotscaper some of the deck's top end is harder to access, which has resulted in dropping Terahertz for good along with freeing up Extra Deck space for Cerberus and another extender in Dharc.  The A Bao+Gryphon line is brutally strong, and being able to go Crypter+Firewall on Cyberse locked lines is also very nice.  I'll talk more in the attached video, but thats the bulk of what i needed to discuss here.

deck_excerpt: Armed Dragon, Armed Dragon Thunder, Dragon Ruler, Combo, Lockdown, Rose Dragon, Level Monster, Level Deck
deck_description:
I have noticed that a lot of fans of this theme tryed to get somewhere with it.
Armed Dragon has been my favorite dragon theme since i'm a beginner and opend my first cards in SOI.
Because the support is very bad it took me years to accomplish this deck before i felt it was good enough to publish it.
The deck has been tested on countless local events with decent results. I think most people just dont know what to do
against it and cannot figure out the choke points in 2-3 games which gives you a pretty good edge here and there.

[DISCLAIMER]:
You will not find the usual cards played relulary with this archetype. Cards like Artilery catapult turtle, spells nor the LV10's are part of the strategy.
This is because of Pile armed Dragons downside which prevents consistant OTK's with this deck but on th eflip side this card has turned out as an amzing combopiece for the deck.
If this way of building is against your imaginations of an Armed Dragon Deck, thats okay. I just tryed to get the most efficent gameplay possible out of these cards. If you are Looking for a Deck with cool Dragons and a unique strategy, soild recovery options that can play with these cards feel free to try it out yourself. Thank you.

The Main combo goes over Pile Armed Dragon . You need it in Hand and 2 Wind Monsters which happens a lot of the time (thats why most Handtraps are WIND too)
So you special summon Pile Armed Dragon  by its own effect (maybe get an Armed Dragon Thunder LV3 off along the way) draw a
nice card along and activate its effect
The good thing is that Pile Armed Dragon  sends an armed dragon Card for cost so Infinite Impermanence  does nothing to prevent that.
With his effect you send Armed Dragon Thunder LV5  to the GY and trigger its effect now you search for Tempest, Dragon Ruler of Storms.
Usually you should have a wind monster to discard to activate Tempest, Dragon Ruler of Storms to search for Red Rose Dragon.
Normal summon Red Rose Dragon  and synch into Bystial Dis Pater (this also works if your level up mechanic gets prevented and you hold a ruler in hand which you can special summon and you didnt used up your normal summon yet with Armed Dragon Blitz)
Now use the effect of Red Rose Dragon to summon out Roxrose Dragon from your Deck and use its search effect to add a copy of Basal Rose Shoot.
You activate it and special summon Red Rose Dragon back to go into Dragunity Knight - Romulus and add Dragon Ravine. 
Now foolish Blaster, Dragon Ruler of Infernos to the GY if possible (any other also does it but blaster is the best choice due to the fire package we are playing).
activate Blaster, Dragon Ruler of Infernos and banish both Red Rose Dragon and Roxrose Dragon to special summon it.
now use Bystial Dis Pater's effect to special summon back to the field one of both and synch into Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying.
Thats the MINIMAL you get out of this combo.
There are also (not so consistent) other possible endboards like Hieratic seal + Avramax locking the opponent out with Amorphage Goliath or Koa'ki Meiru Drago. You can also (if there is another ruler in your hand) link off the Red Rose Dragon into a zone Dragunity Knight - Romulus points to and summon 2 tokens with Mecha Phantom Beast Dracossack which then can be linked into Cherubini, Ebon Angel of the Burning Abyss to floolish Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring depending on the cards you have this could be used for another lv 10 synchro summon into Ruddy Rose Dragon or just be used as link material after you summoned Promethean Princess, Bestower of Flames with Mecha Phantom Beast Dracossack + Cherubini, Ebon Angel of the Burning Abyss. Here you can just pass on Amphibious Swarmship Amblowhale.
The Deck is very versitile and can be used in different ways. Your options can sometimes feel a bit unstable but if you take your time to figure out the options you have, them I'm sure you'll have a lot of fun with this Deck.

Thank you for reading have a nice day!

deck_description:
Ryzeal Beast combines Ritual Beast’s tag-out mechanics, Rank 4 accessibility, and Thunder Dragon Colossus synergy, all while maintaining engine flexibility and consistency. This build incorporates multiple engines that work together seamlessly, enhancing board control, disruption, and follow-up power.

Deck Structure & Engine Balance

This deck is designed to function at 45 cards, which might seem higher than a standard build but is intentional due to the multiple coinciding engines. Rather than diluting consistency, this higher count ensures the necessary cards are available without conflicts, similar to how larger deck counts are structured to support multiple engines without reducing effectiveness.

  • Each engine plays a crucial role, meaning the deck requires more total cards to maintain its flow.
  • A higher count does not mean lower consistency—instead, it ensures that each piece is accessible without overloading certain draws or bricking with redundant cards.
  • The deck remains balanced and efficient, providing consistent hands while maximizing its synergies.

Key Synergies & Card Choices

Rank 4 Accessibility & Extra Deck Flexibility

The deck naturally plays multiple Level 4 monsters, making Rank 4 Xyz plays an effortless part of its strategy.

  • Canna, Pengu, Apelio, and Winda already provide Level 4 Ritual Beast synergy.
  • Ryzeal’s Level 4 bodies fit naturally into the deck’s structure without conflicting with Ritual Beast plays.
  • Bonfire searches either a Ryzeal name or Flag, ensuring the Nemeses engine can be accessed consistently.

This enables access to powerful Rank 4 utility options, such as:

  • Abyss Dweller (graveyard disruption)
  • Tornado Dragon (backrow removal)
  • Other Rank 4 monsters depending on matchup needs

Since Corridor is also Level 4, it serves dual functions, allowing for both overlay plays and Nemeses engine extension.

Pyro & Thunder Typing – Improved Engine Functionality

The Pyro and Thunder typings play a key role in enhancing the deck’s flow:

  • Pyro typing reduces reliance on Banshee since Bonfire can search Flag directly, improving Nemeses engine consistency.
  • Thunder typing increases Colossus synergy, allowing spent Duo Drive to be tributed for Colossus while keeping Corridor as overlay material for further plays.
  • These typings streamline play sequences, ensuring stronger follow-ups and flexible setups without disrupting the Ritual Beast engine.

Duo Drive & Colossus Integration

  • Duo Drive can be tributed for Colossus, making the Thunder Dragon engine a natural fit within the deck’s disruption strategy.
  • Corridor’s Level 4 status allows it to act as Rank 4 overlay material or contribute to the Nemeses engine’s extension.
  • These interactions provide multiple layers of disruption without conflicting with Ritual Beast’s natural playstyle.

Lara for Normal Summon Extension

  • Lara should be used for an initial Normal Summon before committing the actual Normal Summon, ensuring Ice’s effect remains accessible.
  • In Pure Ritual Beast, Lara is typically used as Gaiapelio fodder, but in this hybrid, it extends into Rank 4 plays and additional disruptions.

End-Board Potential

With the added synergy between Ritual Beasts, Nemeses, and Colossus, the deck’s strongest end board consists of:

  • Reirautari, Kimun, or Ulti-Canna with Ritual Beast bodies
  • Thunder Dragon Colossus (via Duo Drive tribute)
  • Detonator
  • Cross in the Field Zone
  • Steeds set for disruption
  • Additional Rank 4s (Dweller, Tornado Dragon, or another Xyz monster depending on the matchup)

This setup ensures:

  • Search denial (Colossus)
  • On-field disruption (Steeds, Detonator, Cross in Field Zone)
  • Strong recursion for follow-up plays

Conclusion

The Ritual Beast + Ryzeal hybrid is a well-balanced deck that efficiently integrates multiple engines without sacrificing consistency or playability. Key takeaways include:

  • The 45-card count is intentional—it allows each engine to function optimally without clashing.
  • Less reliance on Banshee thanks to Bonfire’s ability to search Flag directly.
  • Stronger Rank 4 synergy, making use of existing Level 4 Ritual Beast and Ryzeal monsters.
  • Increased Colossus consistency, ensuring Duo Drive and Corridor interactions remain accessible.

 

By maintaining flexibility, disruption, and strong follow-up potential, this build ensures that each game plan remains intact, making it a versatile and adaptable strategy across different matchups.

deck_excerpt: One of the strongest decks ever conceived in Yugioh... Now in Masterduel!
deck_description:
One of the most ridiculously powerful and consistent decks is now available in Masterduel, and that is Snake-Eyes Azamina Fiendsmith! Consistency is easily available while Fiendsmith cards turbo out Beatrice, which sends any Snake-Eye starter to the GY (most likely Snake-Eyes Ash) then is revived by Promethean Princess! This is in addition to all the other ways to get to your one card combo via the Azamina cards or through the regular Snake-Eyes starters! This enables the deck to include 19 handtraps, 2 Called By and 1 Crossout while having a very high power ceiling! This means that Snake-Eyes can reliably go first or second, powering through with multiple extenders while handtrapping your opponent to oblivion.

Snake-Eyes Azamina Fiendsmith is undoubtably the most powerful deck on ladder right now, and is perfect if you want to tryhard your way to Masters 1 for those sweet sweet gems.

If you want a detailed guide on how to play this deck, check out my earlier article.

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

GLHF Duelists!

First of a kind (unless you count an old Youtube video where someone built Crystron Runick pre new support in MD). Kinda crazy I couldnt find any ressources since Thystvern and Smiger seem like they were made for Hugin.

The goal of the deck is to establish a ressource loop of Sulfador, Inclusion and Eleskeletus, facilitated by the Runick engine. The deck is pretty good both going first and going second (though going second is a bit limited since youre locked into machines and the only way outside of Runicks to break their board are Vermillion Dragon Mech and plan B Ty-Phon). On the plus side, the deck can play well through disruptions because Tristaros is insane.

It can play fine into Fuwalos by ending on Herald + maybe Cluster and Runick Fountain. Shifter kills it but you can at least pitch Smiger/Thystvern for cost to get something and droll hurts a lot but you can still use Tristalos and send Cluster with Sulfador before recovering with Elesketus (similar to combo 2). Biggest issue is honestly Nibiru, but you can try passing before reviving Tristalos to have a play post Nib after siding.

Ametrix is for when you have just Tristalos + Cluster.

Main Combo (Runick + Tristaros/Thystvern): https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=791822-69068034

Combo 2 (Runick + Inclusion/Smiger): https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=791822-69068135

deck_excerpt: The Blue-Eyes meta has finally arrived!
deck_description:
Neo Kaiser Sea Horse's graveyard effect can send the Maiden of White from your deck to your graveyard. You can send him from the field to the graveyard as link material for Spirit with Eyes of Blue to activate his effect.

Bingo Machine, Go!!! is a good early game searcher for Wishes for Eyes of Blue or a Blue-Eyes monster. It's also another late-game search target for Wishes for Eyes of Blue in case you've already used your Majesty of the White Dragons and Roar of the Blue-Eyed Dragons, and you'd need to search for another level 1 light tuner.

This deck plays 5 copies of Aleister the Invoker and Magical Meltdown because seeing more than 1 copy of either card in your starting hand isn't great. Ideally, you'd want to use Aleister and Invocation summon at least 1 Invoked Mechaba over the course of a match. The second copy of Mechaba is great for grindy matches or top deck situations when you've drawn Invocation. Summon Mechaba as soon as possible to protect your plays from hand traps. Aleister is a bridge to the Blue-Eyes archetype because Spirit with Eyes of Blue can use him as link material.

deck_name: Ryzeal FS YCS El Salvador top 16
deck_excerpt: Ryzeal FS YCS El Salvador top 16 EFRAIN SALAZAR
deck_description: Ryzeal FS YCS El Salvador top 16 EFRAIN SALAZAR

As someone who loves the Mitsurugi archetype, I'm tired of seeing it paired up with Ryzeal. However, while I don't like the Ryzeal engine itself, I like what it is capable of, with making King of the Feral Imps then using Eclipse Twins to resummon it to hit the full Mitsurugi. So, I thought to myself, "How can I achieve this without using those little engines?" Then I remembered my cursed Exosister Pile deck and found exactly what I needed.

Using the Superheavy engine or a mini Shark engine with Surfacing Big Jaws to start and extend with the Springans engine is so satisfying to me. Especially because the combo isn't locked into Rank 4 Xyz's whihc allows to boards to end on I:P to make Dyna Mondo on the opponent's turn and potentially Gigantic Sargas for a pop/bounce, dpeneding on the Xyz monster you end on.

Now, this weird variant may not be Mitsurugi Ryzeal, but it gets the job done surprisingly well and doesn't burn a hole in your pocket, though I'm still holding out for Mitsurugi Ritual reprints.
